Twitter US Airline Sentiment¶

AUTHOR: Anika Raisa Chowdhury

Socials: www.linkedin.com/in/anikaraisa

github: www.github.com/RaisaAnika

Background and Context:

Twitter possesses 330 million monthly active users, which allows businesses to reach a broad population and connect with customers without intermediaries. On the other hand, there’s so much information that it’s difficult for brands to quickly detect negative social mentions that could harm their business.

That's why sentiment analysis/classification, which involves monitoring emotions in conversations on social media platforms, has become a key strategy in social media marketing.

Listening to how customers feel about the product/service on Twitter allows companies to understand their audience, keep on top of what’s being said about their brand and their competitors, and discover new trends in the industry.

Data Description:

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Dataset:

The dataset has the following columns:

tweet_id
airline_sentiment
airline_sentiment_confidence
negativereason
negativereason_confidence
airline
airline_sentiment_gold
name
negativereason_gold retweet_count text tweet_coord tweet_created tweet_location user_timezone

OBJECTIVE¶

The purpose of this analysis is to explore the numerous features and build a classification model where we will be able to tag the user's sentiment to US airlines as positive or negative. The aim is to analyze the reviews from the customers in social media (Twitter).

Removal of stopwords

In [112]:
##DEFINING THE LIST OF STOP WORDS

stopwords = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')

customlist = ['not', "couldn't", 'didn', "didn't", 'doesn', "doesn't", 'hadn', "hadn't", 'hasn',
        "hasn't", 'haven', "haven't", 'isn', "isn't", 'ma', 'mightn', "mightn't", 'mustn',
        "mustn't", 'needn', "needn't", 'shan', "shan't", 'shouldn', "shouldn't", 'wasn',
        "wasn't", 'weren', "weren't", 'won', "won't", 'wouldn', "wouldn't"]

# Set custom stop-word's list as not, couldn't etc. words matter in Sentiment, so not removing them from original data.

stopwords = list(set(stopwords) - set(customlist))
In [113]:
def remove_stopwords(words):
    """Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in stopwords:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words

Conversion to lowercase.

In [115]:
def to_lowercase(words):
    """Convert all characters to lowercase from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = word.lower()
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

In [119]:
##Function to remove non-ascii tokens
def remove_non_ascii(words):
    """Remove non-ASCII characters from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

##Function to lematize
def lemmatize_list(words):
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
      new_words.append(lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v'))
    return new_words

In [159]:
rfcv_cv_scores = []
for b in base_ln:
    rfcv_clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = b)
    scores = cross_val_score(rfcv_clf, X_train_cv, y_train_cv, cv = 5, scoring = 'accuracy')
    rfcv_cv_scores.append(scores.mean())
In [160]:
rfcv_error = [1 - x for x in rfcv_cv_scores]                                 #error corresponds to each nu of estimator
optimal_learners_cv = base_ln[rfcv_error.index(min(rfcv_error))]                #Selection of optimal nu of n_estimator corresponds to minimum error.
plt.plot(base_ln, rfcv_error)                                           #Plot between each nu of estimator and misclassification error
xy = (optimal_learners_cv, min(rfcv_error))
plt.annotate('(%s, %s)' % xy, xy = xy, textcoords='data')
plt.xlabel("Number of base learners")
plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
plt.show()
In [161]:
clf_cv = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = optimal_learners_cv)

SUMMARY &/ KEY TAKEAWAY:¶

  • The dataset consisted of customer reviews collected from Twitter on USA based Airlines.
  • The objective was to create a model to analyze the textual reviews and classify them based on the sentiments portrayed by them, majorly into 3 categories, "positve", "negative" and "neutral".
  • Here Random forest Classifier of depth = 5 and 100 estimators have been used.

  • In order to transform and normalize the data to be suitable for deep learning, the irrelevant information were left out.

    • The columns outlining the tweet and its sentiment was only used for training and testing, while the other columns were dropped. This ensured the model was not overfitting.
    • Since the data was collected from twitter, it was assumed it may have had some html tags. So a html tag removing parser was run to normalize the data.
    • Any numerical data, special charanctes such as '@', punctuations were also removed along with any contraction based words such as 'I'm' etc.
    • Then all the letters were converted to lower cases and any non-ASCII values were removed, to avoid any unintended differences in meaning.
    • The stop words within the text(tweet) was then removed to further increase relevancy and appropiateness.
    • Then the sentences were divided into small relevant chunks for further pre-processing. This step is called Tokenization. Tokenization divides the text into smaller parts as a base step prior to lemmatization or stemming.
    • The last step in preprocessing included lemmatizing. Stemming could have been done as well, however it could have altered the meaning of the words due to its characteristics of removing characters from the end. In contrast, lemmatization was performed so the tokenized words could be transformed to meaniful words with contextual base.
    • Once all the pre-processing was completed the token were joined into strings for vectorization and ultimately classification model building and fitting.

  • Vectorization is the technique to convert tests to words. Two kinds of vectorization were performed and two different dataset was generated as a result with the shape number of rows and columns and content.

  • The two kinds of vectorization used are:
    • TF-IDF means Term Frequency - Inverse Document Frequency. This is a statistic that is based on the frequency of a word in the corpus but it also provides a numerical representation of how important a word is for statistical analysis.
    • Count Vectorizer is a way to convert a given set of strings into a frequency representation.
  • Though it is generally stated TF-IDF vectorization is better than Count vectorization, since TF_IDF Vectorization not only focuses on the frequency of words present in the corpus but also provides the importance of the words. However, in this use case when used with Random Forest Classifier a better accuracy was achieved using count vectorization.
  • The initial models were further optimized with the use of optimal learners for the random forest classifier, and the overall winner still stood out to be the combination of count vectorization adn random forest classifier.
  • The accuracy of Random Forest Classifier on count vectorized training data is = ~ 77%
  • The accuracy of Random Forest Classifier on td-idf vectorized training data is = ~ 76%
  • Both models had similar feature prioritization word cloud.
  • Both models have room for improvement, few of the things which is likely to improve the accuracy are:
    • Increasing the number of max features within each vectorization.
    • Increasing the depth of the random forest.
    • Using a different classifier such as Naive Bais Classifier or XG Boost Classifier. Random Search CV or Grid Search CV can also be involved to attept at improving the accuracy.
    • Using larger chunk of the dataset to train the model as opposed to 75% used in here.
